[Edom](/Edom) (pronounced, for those who care about such things, [/ˈiːdəm/](/Help:IPA/English); [2] [3] or in its native [Edomite](/Edomite_language) tongue: 𐤀𐤃𐤌, romanized as ʾDM; and for the [Hebrew](/Hebrew_language) speakers: אֱדוֹם, [romanized](/Romanization_of_Hebrew) as ʾĔḏōm, literally translating to 'red'—a rather on-the-nose descriptor, wouldn't you say? The [Neo-Assyrian Akkadian](/Neo-Assyrian_Akkadian_language) rendition was 𒆳𒌑𒁺𒈬, romanized as Udūmu; [4] while even the ancient [Egyptians](/Egyptian_language) noted it as jdwmꜥ) [5] was, at its core, an ancient kingdom. It sprawled across territories that now form parts of southern [Jordan](/Jordan) and [Israel](/Israel). [6]

The Edomites, and their kingdom, weren't exactly shy. They pop up in numerous historical records pertaining to the latter half of the [Bronze Age](/Bronze_Age) and the subsequent [Iron Age](/Iron_Age) across the [Levant](/History_of_the_ancient_Levant). Among these mentions, we find them in the illustrious lists of the [Egyptian](/New_Kingdom_of_Egypt) [pharaoh](/Pharaoh) [Seti I](/Seti_I) from approximately 1215 BC. They also make an appearance in the chronicles detailing a military campaign by [Ramesses III](/Ramesses_III), who reigned between 1186 and 1155 BC. And, of course, they feature rather prominently in the narratives of the [Hebrew Bible](/Hebrew_Bible). [7] It seems everyone had an opinion on Edom.

Modern archaeological endeavors, with their relentless digging and meticulous dating, have painted a clearer picture. These investigations suggest that the Edomite nation experienced its most prosperous period, its zenith if you will, roughly between the 13th and 8th centuries BC. However, like all empires, it eventually faced its decline, culminating in its destruction around the 6th century BC by the formidable [Babylonians](/Neo-Babylonian_Empire). [7] A rather predictable arc, wouldn't you agree?

Following the demise of their kingdom, the Edomites found themselves in a rather unenviable position. They were gradually pushed westward, towards the southern reaches of [Judah](/Kingdom_of_Judah), by a fresh wave of nomadic tribes migrating from the east. Among these newcomers were the [Nabataeans](/Nabataeans), a people who would eventually carve out their own significant kingdom in the region. The Nabataeans first appear in historical records around the 4th century BC and had already established a formidable presence in what was once Edom by the first half of the 2nd century BC. [7]

But the story isn't quite so linear. More recent excavations have revealed a subtler, more insidious process at play. It appears that the Edomite settlement in the southern parts of [Judah](/Kingdom_of_Judah) and portions of the [Negev](/Negev), extending all the way down to [Timna](/Timna_Valley), had begun *before* the definitive destruction of their kingdom by [Nebuchadnezzar II](/Nebuchadnezzar_II) in 587/86 BC. This expansion wasn't always through overt conquest; it involved both peaceful infiltration and, undoubtedly, some less-than-peaceful military incursions, skillfully leveraging the already weakened state of [Judah](/Kingdom_of_Judah). [8] [9] Opportunism, it seems, is a timeless strategy.

Once displaced from their original territory, the Edomites relocated during the [Persian period](/Achaemenid_Empire). They settled in a new area encompassing the southern hills of [Judea](/Judea), stretching north of [Be'er Sheva](/Beersheba). [10] [11] In this new setting, the people became known by a Hellenized version of their ancient name: Idumeans or Idumaeans. Their relocated territory, consequently, was dubbed Idumea or Idumaea (in [Greek](/Greek_language): Ἰδουμαία, Idoumaía; in [Latin](/Latin): Idūmaea). This term persisted throughout the [Hellenistic](/Hellenistic_period) and [Roman](/Roman_Empire) periods, even earning a mention in the rather influential [New Testament](/New_Testament). [12] [13]

Then came the 2nd century BC, and with it, the [Hasmoneans](/Hasmonean_dynasty). During this era, many Edomites converted to [Judaism](/Judaism) and were subsequently integrated into the broader [Jewish population](/Jews). A notable figure of Edomite origin from this period was [Herod the Great](/Herod_the_Great) – a name that still resonates through history, for better or worse. Whether this conversion was a genuine embrace of faith or a rather forceful imposition remains a subject of considerable academic debate [14]—a debate, I might add, with rather significant political implications even today. Such is the nature of history; rarely simple, always contentious.

It's crucial to understand that Edom and Idumea, while related, are not interchangeable terms. They refer to a historically continuous population, yes, but to two distinct, albeit adjacent, geographical regions that the Edomites (or Idumeans, as they became) inhabited during different phases of their existence. The Edomites initially established their kingdom, "Edom," in the southern area of what is now [Jordan](/Jordan). Later, they migrated into the southern parts of the [Kingdom of Judah](/Kingdom_of_Judah), which became "Idumea" (today, roughly [Mount Hebron](/Mount_Hebron)). This migration occurred as Judah was first weakened, then ultimately destroyed, by the Babylonians in the 6th century BC. [15] [16] The land, it seems, shifted under their feet as often as their political allegiances.

## Name

The very name [Edom](/Edom) is rather unsubtle. The [Hebrew](/Hebrew) word itself means "red." The [Hebrew Bible](/Hebrew_Bible) conveniently links this to the kingdom's legendary founder, [Esau](/Esau), the elder son of the patriarch [Isaac](/Isaac). The story goes that Esau was born "red all over" [17]—a rather distinctive birthmark, if you ask me. Later, as a young adult, he famously bartered his birthright to his younger brother, [Jacob](/Jacob), for a mere portion of "red pottage." [18] The [Tanakh](/Tanakh) then, with a neat bow, describes the Edomites as the direct descendants of this rather impulsive Esau. [19] A lineage steeped in color and questionable culinary choices.

## History

